@Donny Brook I lived it for 16 years I saw alot... 
You really see what a person is made of on a trawler....  Its a test... Being a decky is hard... Its tough as it gets.... Being the Captain is harder...  Im very proud of the fact I've got all my fingers and toes... and I lost no boats or crew in my career....  I talk to my freinds still doing it , occasionally....  Its still the same... Though its a lot more regulated these days....  My freind anchored up a year or so ago... Whilst asleep he and the crew went to the bottom... dead. 
Another freind from many years ago who refuses to step on a boat again woke up one night in the water as the boat hooked up in a following sea and the ocean just rolled over it , he was ejected thru the focsil hatch by the pressure 36 hrs later he washed ashore,  by chance he found a Japanese glass float an hour into his ordeal...  I could go on and on about the carnage the fishery I worked in.... Not for the faint hearted....  But I liked it... Family matters cut my career short....  Could go back to it tommorrow if wanted but that era passed in my life... I miss it though.

